# {{.Feature}} — a gopernicus feature

Scaffolded by `gopernicus new feature`. A datastore-free, view-free feature
module carrying one aggregate, **{{.Agg}}**, with a create/get/list/delete
use-case set. Born conforming to the feature charter (`features/README.md`) — a
placeholder you rename and grow.

## Layout

```
{{.Feature}}.go                     the FS2 socket: Repositories, Config, NewService, Service, Register
domain/{{.Agg}}/                    the public rim: entity, Storer port, order allow-list
internal/logic/{{.AggSvc}}/         the sealed service (create/get/list/delete)
storetest/                          the exported conformance suite (Run)
memstore/                           the in-core reference Storer (hermetic proof + storetest target)
stores/turso/                       the Turso/libSQL store adapter (its own module)
stores/pgx/                         the PostgreSQL store adapter (its own module)
```

## Charter checklist trace (features/README.md §8)

| # | item | where |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | compiles standalone with its own go.mod | `go build ./...` |
| 2 | go.mod requires sdk only (FS1) | `go.mod` |
| 4 | FS2 trio: NewService / Service / Register | `{{.Feature}}.go` |
| 5 | each store: Repositories(db) + ExportMigrations | `stores/{turso,pgx}` |
| 6 | zero-infra proof (in-memory Repositories) | `memstore/` |
| 10 | storetest suite + reference passes it | `storetest/`, `memstore/conformance_test.go` |
| 11 | both {turso, pgx} stores exist and pass storetest | `stores/{turso,pgx}` |
| 13 | order allow-list + DefaultOrder + ListLimits; six-case family | `domain/{{.Agg}}/order.go`, `storetest/` |
| 14 | Config.IDs threaded to the entity constructor; DBGeneratedIDOnEmpty | `{{.Feature}}.go`, `storetest/` |

Items 3, 7, 8, 9, 12 hold by construction (no cross-feature imports, no init(),
documented nil semantics). Fill route-surface docs (item 7) when you add an
inbound adapter.

## Pre-tag wiring

gopernicus publishes no version tags yet, so `go get` cannot resolve the
`github.com/gopernicus/gopernicus/*` modules. Until `v0.1.0` is cut, point each
at a local checkout of the gopernicus repo:

```
# core module
go mod edit -replace github.com/gopernicus/gopernicus/sdk=/abs/path/to/gopernicus/sdk
go mod tidy

# each store module (from stores/turso and stores/pgx)
go mod edit -replace github.com/gopernicus/gopernicus/sdk=/abs/path/to/gopernicus/sdk
go mod edit -replace {{.ModuleRoot}}/... # (the core resolves via the emitted ../.. replace)
go mod tidy
```

## Wiring this feature into a host

The feature reaches a host through the narrow `feature.Mount` + `Register`
surface — no init() registration, no service locator. In your host's
composition root:

```go
import (
	{{.Feature}} "{{.ModulePath}}"
	"{{.ModulePath}}/memstore"          // or a store adapter's Repositories(db)
	"github.com/gopernicus/gopernicus/sdk/feature"
)

repos := {{.Feature}}.Repositories{ {{.ReposField}}: memstore.New{{.ReposField}}() }
svc, err := {{.Feature}}.NewService(repos, {{.Feature}}.Config{})
if err != nil {
	return err
}
svc.Register(feature.Mount{Router: router, Logger: log})

// Register mounts no routes (skeleton). Reach use-cases directly:
created, err := svc.Create(ctx, "first {{.Agg}}")
page, err := svc.List(ctx, {{.Feature}}.ListFilter{}, crud.ListRequest{})
```

For a persistent host, swap the memstore for a store adapter:

```go
repos, err := turso.Repositories(db)   // or pgx.Repositories(db)
```

## Migrations (scaffold-and-own)

Store adapters expose canonical SQL and `ExportMigrations`, but the **host** owns
its migration tree. Scaffold this feature's SQL into your host's ledger and apply
it pre-boot — the framework never migrates at startup:

```go
turso.ExportMigrations("workshop/migrations/primary")   // or pgx.ExportMigrations(...)
```

Both dialect trees carry an identical migration version set (`0001_{{.Agg}}.sql`);
the host resolves any filename conflicts in its own directory.

## Rename it

The `{{.Agg}}` aggregate and its single `Name` field are placeholders. To model a
real aggregate: edit `domain/{{.Agg}}/{{.Agg}}.go` (entity + fields), extend the
`Storer` port and the service, mirror the columns in both stores' row structs and
`migrations/0001_{{.Agg}}.sql`, and add cases to `storetest`. The SQL table is
named `{{.Agg}}` — rename it if it collides with a reserved word.
